Q1. üß© What is the meaning of sorted?
Sorted means arranged in a specific order either of numbers,strings,objects etc. sorted happens in two ways :
-> ascending order (smallest to largest) : 1, 2, 3, 5, 8
-> descending order ( largest to smalles ) : 8, 5, 3, 2, 1


Types of Sorting :
------------------

1. Bubble Sort :- 
üëâ Compares two numbers at a time and swaps them if they are in the wrong order.
It keeps doing this again and again until everything is sorted.
Example:
List: 5, 3, 2
         Compare 5 & 3 ‚Üí swap ‚Üí 3, 5, 2
        Compare 5 & 2 ‚Üí swap ‚Üí 3, 2, 5
        Compare 3 & 2 ‚Üí swap ‚Üí 2, 3, 5
‚úÖ Final: 2, 3, 5
             üîπ Steps: To Implement Bubble Sort.
                                             1Ô∏è‚É£ Run the outer loop from 0 to n-1.  (because jab 1 element hogi adjacent ke liye or baki adjast ho chuke honge to koi sense nhi bnta usko adjust krke becoz already wo shi order me hoga.)
                                             2Ô∏è‚É£ Inside it, run an inner loop from 0 to n-i-1. (Each pass pushes the largest element to the end.)
                                             3Ô∏è‚É£ Compare adjacent elements:
                                                                    If arr[j] > arr[j+1], then swap them.
                                             4Ô∏è‚É£ Repeat until the entire array is sorted.
‚úÖ Time Complexity: O(n¬≤), Space Complexity: O(1)

follow up question :
int [] arr = {5,3,2,1,9,8}; // 1,2,3,5,8,9



2. Insertion Sort
üëâwe assume array into parts one is sorted and another one unsorted so from unsorted part Takes one number at a time and inserts it in the correct place among the sorted ones.
Example:
List: 3, 1, 2
         Start with 3 (already sorted)
         Insert 1 before 3 ‚Üí 1, 3
         Insert 2 between 1 and 3 ‚Üí 1, 2, 3
‚úÖ Final: 1, 2, 3
         üß© Step-by-Step Implementation Explanation :
                                           Step 1: Start with the second element :
                                                             - We assume the first element of the array is already sorted.
                                                             - So, we start from index 1 (the second element).
                                           Step 2: Store the current element :
                                                             - Take the current element (say temp = arr[i]) from the unsorted part.
                                                             - This is the element we want to insert into the sorted part.
                                           Step 3: Compare and shift :
                                                             - Initialize a pointer j = i - 1 (the last index of the sorted part).
                                                             - While j >= 0 and arr[j] > temp:
                                                                                      Shift the element arr[j] one position to the right (arr[j + 1] = arr[j]).
                                                                                      Decrease j by 1 to continue checking previous elements.
                                           Step 4: Insert the element :
                                                             - When the correct position is found (loop stops), insert the temp element at that position:  arr[j + 1] = temp.
                                           Step 5: Repeat :
                                                             - Move to the next element in the array (i++) and repeat steps until all elements are sorted.
‚úÖ Time Complexity = O(n2)

follow up question :
 int [] arr = {8,4,1,5,9,2}; //  1 2 4 5 8 9 



3. Selection Sort :- 
üëâwe assume array into parts one is sorted and another one unsorted where Initially, we assume the entire array is unsorted and the sorted part is empty.so from unsorted part Finds the smallest number,
Fir us smallest element ko unsorted part ke first element ke sath swap kar dete hain Isse smallest element sorted part me chala jata hai Ye process tab tak repeat karte hain jab tak pura array sorted na ho jaye.
Example:
List: 4, 2, 1, 3
             Smallest is 1 ‚Üí put it first ‚Üí 1, 2, 4, 3
            Next smallest is 2 ‚Üí already in place
            Next smallest is 3 ‚Üí swap with 4
‚úÖ Final: 1, 2, 3, 4
               ‚öôÔ∏è Steps to Implement Selection Sort : 
                                              1Ô∏è‚É£ Start outer loop ‚Üí
                                                        Run i from 0 to n-1 because if there will be remaining one element so by default that will be in it's position.
                                              2Ô∏è‚É£  assuming the first unsorted element is the smallest ‚Üí
                                                        Set min = i,  Assume current index as minimum.
                                              3Ô∏è‚É£ Search for smaller element ‚Üí
                                                        Run inner loop j from i+1 to n to find the actual smallest element‚Äôs index.
                                              4Ô∏è‚É£ Compare & Update minimum index ‚Üí
                                                        If any arr[j] < arr[min], update min = j.
                                              5Ô∏è‚É£ after inner loop do Swaping ‚Üí
                                                        After the inner loop, swap arr[i] with arr[min] if min != i.
                                              6Ô∏è‚É£ Repeat the process ‚Üí
                                                        Continue until all elements are placed in their correct positions.
                                              7Ô∏è‚É£ Result ‚Üí
                                                        Array becomes sorted in ascending order.

‚úÖ Time Complexity = O(n2)


4. Brick Sort :
Brick Sort ek comparison-based sorting algorithm hai jo array ko pair-wise compare karke sort karta hai similar to bubble sort but in this we compare indexes‚Äî
pehle odd index pairs compare karta hai, fir even index pairs, aur ye process tab tak chalta rehta hai jab tak array sorted nahi ho jata.
Isse Odd-Even Sort bhi kehte hain ya fir parity sort.
                       ‚öôÔ∏è Steps to Implement Brick Sort :
                                              1Ô∏è‚É£ Repeat until no swap happens ‚Üí
                                                           Hum overall loop tab tak chalate hain jab tak poora array sorted nahi ho jata.
                                                           Ek boolean flag use karte hain: isSorted = false; then while(!isSorted) { isSorted= true) both loop inside it}.
                                              2Ô∏è‚É£ Odd Phase ‚Üí Compare odd-index pairs
                                                            Odd phase me hum (index 1,2), (3,4), (5,6) ko compare karte hain:
                                                             for (int i = 1; i <= n-2; i += 2)
                                                                      if(arr[i] > arr[i+1])
                                                                          swap(arr[i], arr[i+1])
                                                                          isSorted=false;
                                              3Ô∏è‚É£ Even Phase ‚Üí Compare even-index pairs
                                                             Even phase me hum (index 0,1), (2,3), (4,5) ko compare karte hain:
                                                                for (int i = 0; i <= n-2; i += 2)
                                                                     if(arr[i] > arr[i+1])
                                                                        swap(arr[i], arr[i+1])
                                                                          isSorted=false;
                                              4Ô∏è‚É£ If no swaps in both phases ‚Üí sorted
                                                              Agar odd + even phases me ek bhi swap nahi hua ‚Üí array sorted.
                                              5Ô∏è‚É£ Continue until sorted
                                                              Odd ‚Üí Even ‚Üí Odd ‚Üí Even repeatedly Jab tak array sorted nahi ho jaye.
                                              6Ô∏è‚É£ Final Result ‚Üí
                                                             Example: 4,3,2,1
                                                             After many odd/even rounds ‚Üí 1,2,3,4
‚úÖ Time Complexity = O(n2)


5.Counting Sort Algorithm :
üëâ Counting Sort ek non-comparison based sorting algorithm hai. Yeh algorithm elements ko count karke sort karta hai.
Matlab har number kitni baar aya hai, woh count karte hain, fir us count ko use karke final sorted array banate hain.
- Isme compare nahi karna padta, balki frequency count calculate hoti hai.
- Counting sort tab fast hota hai jab array ke numbers 0 to k range me ho (k bahut bada na ho).
- bahut bada array, negative numbers ke liye ye sorting kam nhi krta.
Example:
List: 4, 2, 2, 1, 3
Range = 0 to 4
Step 1: Count frequency
0 ‚Üí 0
1 ‚Üí 1
2 ‚Üí 2
3 ‚Üí 1
4 ‚Üí 1
Step 2: According to counts, final sorted array:
1, 2, 2, 3, 4
‚öôÔ∏è Steps to Implement Counting Sort :
                                1Ô∏è‚É£ Find the maximum element ‚Üí
                                                Because counting array ka size hum maximum element ke according banate hain.
                                                         Example:
                                                         arr = {4, 2, 2, 1, 3}
                                                         max = 4
                                2Ô∏è‚É£ Create a count array ‚Üí
                                                         Size = max + 1
                                                         Initialize all to zero. in java by default all are zero don't need extra work
                                                         Example:
                                                         count[0..4] = {0, 0, 0, 0, 0}
                                3Ô∏è‚É£ Count occurrences of each number ‚Üí
                                                Har element ke liye: count[arr[i]] = count[arr[i]]+1;
                                                After counting:  count = {0,1,2,1,1}
                                4Ô∏è‚É£ Build the sorted output using count ‚Üí
                                                Jitni baar koi number aaya hai, utni baar output me add karo.
                                                         Example:
                                                         1 ‚Üí 1 time
                                                         2 ‚Üí 2 times
                                                         3 ‚Üí 1 time
                                                         4 ‚Üí 1 time
                                                         Final: 1, 2, 2, 3, 4
                                5Ô∏è‚É£ Copy back to original array ‚Üí
                                                Jo sorted output bn chuki, use original array me copy kar do.
                                6Ô∏è‚É£ Result ‚Üí
                                             Array sorted in ascending order without comparisons. Final Output: 1, 2, 2, 3, 4
‚è±Ô∏è Time Complexity:
Counting Sort = O(n + k)
Where:
n = number of elements
k = maximum value in array


                                            

